** Chapter 1 - Setting Up the Environment
This Chapter is only concerned with the Basic Setup
** Chapter 2 - Creating a First Database

Firs we create the ~Database~ =Analysis=
#+name: chapter-2
#+header: :engine postgres
#+header: :dbhost localhost
#+header: :dbuser sebastian
#+header: :database analysis
#+begin_src sql
  CREATE DATABASE analysis;   
#+end_src

Then we add the Table named =teachers=
#+name: chapter-2-1
#+header: :engine postgres
#+header: :dbhost localhost
#+header: :dbuser sebastian
#+header: :database analysis
#+begin_src sql
  CREATE TABLE teachers (
      id bigserial,
      first_name varchar(25),
      last_name varchar(50),
      school varchar(50),
      hire_date date,
      salary numeric
  );
#+end_src

#+RESULTS: chapter-2-1
| CREATE TABLE |
|--------------|

*** Finding Distinct Values
Querying *distinct values* in the =school= column

#+NAME: chapter-3-4-1
#+HEADER: :engine postgres
#+HEADER: :database analysis

  FROM teachers
  ORDER BY school;

|---------------------|
| F.D. Roosevelt HS   |
| Myers Middle School |

#+HEADER: :engine postgres
#+HEADER: :database analysis

  SELECT *
  FROM teachers
  WHERE last_name = 'Cole'

|----+------------+-----------+---------------------+------------+--------|
|  3 | Samuel     | Cole      | Myers Middle School | 2005-08-01 |  43500 |
|  4 | Samantha   | Bush      | Myers Middle School | 2011-10-30 |  36200 |
|  9 | Samuel     | Cole      | Myers Middle School | 2005-08-01 |  43500 |
| 10 | Samantha   | Bush      | Myers Middle School | 2011-10-30 |  36200 |

#+NAME: chapter-3-7-3
#+HEADER: :engine postgres
#+HEADER: :database analysis

**** US Census Data
***** CREATE TABLE statement for Census county population estimates
Data dictionary for estimates available at: [[https://www2.census.gov/programs-surveys/popest/technical-documentation/file-layouts/2010-2019/co-est2019-alldata.pdf][Census.gov: Surveys - Counties 2019]]
Data dictionary for additional columns at: http://www.census.gov/prod/cen2010/doc/pl94-171.pdf
:NOTE:
Some columns have been given more descriptive names
:END:

#+NAME: chapter-5-1-1
#+HEADER: :engine postgres
#+HEADER: :database analysis
#+begin_src sql
  CREATE TABLE us_counties_pop_est_2019 (
      state_fips text,                         -- State FIPS code
      county_fips text,                        -- County FIPS code
      region smallint,                         -- Region
      state_name text,                         -- State name	
      county_name text,                        -- County name
      area_land bigint,                        -- Area (Land) in square meters
      area_water bigint,                       -- Area (Water) in square meters
      internal_point_lat numeric(10,7),        -- Internal point (latitude)
      internal_point_lon numeric(10,7),        -- Internal point (longitude)
      pop_est_2018 integer,                    -- 2018-07-01 resident total population estimate
      pop_est_2019 integer,                    -- 2019-07-01 resident total population estimate
      births_2019 integer,                     -- Births from 2018-07-01 to 2019-06-30
      deaths_2019 integer,                     -- Deaths from 2018-07-01 to 2019-06-30
      international_migr_2019 integer,         -- Net international migration from 2018-07-01 to 2019-06-30
      domestic_migr_2019 integer,              -- Net domestic migration from 2018-07-01 to 2019-06-30
      residual_2019 integer,                   -- Residual for 2018-07-01 to 2019-06-30
      CONSTRAINT counties_2019_key PRIMARY KEY (state_fips, county_fips)	
  );
#+end_src

#+NAME: chapter-6-2-4
#+HEADER: :engine postgres
#+HEADER: :dbhost localhost
#+HEADER: :dbuser sebastian
#+HEADER: :database analysis
#+begin_src sql
  SELECT county_name AS county,
	 state_name AS state,
	 pop_est_2019 AS pop,
	 pop_est_2018 + births_2019 - deaths_2019 + 
	     international_migr_2019 + domestic_migr_2019 +
	     residual_2019 AS components_total,
	 pop_est_2019 - (pop_est_2018 + births_2019 - deaths_2019 + 
	     international_migr_2019 + domestic_migr_2019 +
	     residual_2019) AS difference
  FROM us_counties_pop_est_2019
  ORDER BY difference DESC;
#+end_src

*** Calculating percent change
#+NAME: chapter-6-3-1
#+HEADER: :engine postgres
#+HEADER: :dbhost localhost
#+HEADER: :dbuser sebastian
#+HEADER: :database analysis
#+begin_src sql
  CREATE TABLE percent_change (
      department text,
      spend_2019 numeric(10,2),
      spend_2022 numeric(10,2)
  );
#+end_src

#+RESULTS: chapter-6-3-1
| CREATE TABLE |
|--------------|

#+NAME: chapter-6-3-2
#+HEADER: :engine postgres
#+HEADER: :dbhost localhost
#+HEADER: :dbuser sebastian
#+HEADER: :database analysis
#+begin_src sql
  INSERT INTO percent_change
  VALUES
      ('Assessor', 178556, 179500),
      ('Building', 250000, 289000),
      ('Clerk', 451980, 650000),
      ('Library', 87777, 90001),
      ('Parks', 250000, 223000),
      ('Water', 199000, 195000);
#+end_src

#+RESULTS: chapter-6-3-2
| INSERT 0 6 |
|------------|

#+NAME: chapter-6-3-4
#+HEADER: :engine postgres
#+HEADER: :dbhost localhost
#+HEADER: :dbuser sebastian
#+HEADER: :database analysis
#+begin_src sql
  SELECT department,
	 spend_2019,
	 spend_2022,
	 round( (spend_2022 - spend_2019) /
		      spend_2019 * 100, 1) AS pct_change
  FROM percent_change;
#+end_src

**** Calculating the percent of a county's area that is water

#+HEADER: :engine postgres
#+HEADER: :dbhost localhost
#+HEADER: :dbuser sebastian
#+HEADER: :database analysis
#+begin_src sql
  SELECT county_name AS county,
	 state_name AS state,
	 area_water::numeric / (area_land + area_water) * 100 AS pct_water
  FROM us_counties_pop_est_2019
  ORDER BY pct_water DESC;

*** Testing SQL percentile functions

#+NAME: chapter-6-5-1
#+HEADER: :engine postgres
#+HEADER: :dbhost localhost
#+HEADER: :dbuser sebastian
#+HEADER: :database analysis
#+begin_src sql
  CREATE TABLE percentile_test (
	numbers integer
  );

  INSERT INTO percentile_test (numbers) VALUES
      (1), (2), (3), (4), (5), (6);

  SELECT
      percentile_cont(.5)
      WITHIN GROUP (ORDER BY numbers),
      percentile_disc(.5)
      WITHIN GROUP (ORDER BY numbers)
  FROM percentile_test;
#+end_src

#+RESULTS: chapter-6-5-1
| CREATE TABLE    |                 |
|-----------------+-----------------|
| INSERT 0 6      |                 |
| percentile_cont | percentile_disc |
| 3.5             |               3 |

#+NAME: chapter-6-P3-C
#+HEADER: :engine postgres
#+HEADER: :database analysis
#+begin_src sql
  SELECT state_name,
	 percentile_cont(0.5)
	    WITHIN GROUP (ORDER BY pop_est_2019) AS median
  FROM us_counties_pop_est_2019
  GROUP BY state_name;	
#+end_src
